# trivy .trivyignore — suppressions for findings that are false positives for
# this chart/image. Read automatically by `trivy config`/`trivy image` from the
# repo root. One check ID per line; `#` lines are comments/justifications.
#
# Real container-hardening findings (KSV-0020/KSV-0021, runAsUser/runAsGroup >
# 10000) are FIXED in values.yaml, not ignored.

# KSV-0109 / KSV-01010 — "ConfigMap stores secrets / sensitive contents".
# FALSE POSITIVE: the rendered config.yaml contains only ${ENV} placeholders for
# secret fields (e.g. client_secret: "${TS_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET}"), never real
# secret values. Actual secret VALUES are injected via the Kubernetes Secret +
# envFrom and expanded at runtime; the chart's `secret:` block is the supported
# path for real secret values. trivy flags the placeholder key NAMES, not data.
KSV-0109
KSV-01010

# KSV-0110 — "resource in default namespace".
# FALSE POSITIVE: the namespace is chosen at deploy time (`helm -n <ns>` /
# `--namespace`); the chart never hardcodes metadata.namespace to `default`.
KSV-0110

# KSV-0125 — "image from an untrusted registry".
# FALSE POSITIVE: ghcr.io/rknightion/tailscale2otel is the project's own
# first-party publish registry, cosign keyless-signed via GitHub OIDC (see
# deploy/CLAUDE.md release/publish pipelines).
KSV-0125

# DS-0026 — "no HEALTHCHECK instruction".
# FALSE POSITIVE: the binary has NO always-on HTTP listener; its health endpoint
# (/healthz) is opt-in and only served when admin.enabled is set. A Dockerfile
# HEALTHCHECK hitting it would mark every default (admin-disabled) container
# unhealthy. Operators who enable the admin server can add a compose/k8s probe;
# the Helm chart already wires /healthz + /readyz when admin is enabled.
DS-0026
